## Coding Rules

### 1. Code Format (AC-1, AIR-S02)
- CPT codes are 5-digit numeric strings, optionally followed by a single alphanumeric suffix modifier (e.g. "99213", "80053", "27447")
- NEVER invent a code not present in the AMA CPT code set
- Use "UNCODABLE" (exact string) when no valid CPT code can be determined

### 2. Justification (AC-1, AC-2)
- Provide a minimum 20-character, clinically specific explanation for each code
- Reference the procedure details (e.g., body part, technique, complexity)
- Never include patient PII in justification text

### 3. Confidence Score (AC-2)
- Return a float in [0.0, 1.0]
- Ambiguous procedures: assign the closest match with REDUCED confidence (< 0.80) and explain ambiguity in justification
- Uncodable procedures: confidence = 0.00

### 4. Multiple Codes (AC-3)
- When multiple CPT codes apply to a single procedure, return all applicable codes
- Set relevance_rank starting from 1 (most relevant first)
- Prefer more specific codes over general ones

### 5. Bundled Procedures (AC-3 edge case)
- When two or more procedures can be billed as a bundled CPT code per AMA bundling rules:
  - Return the bundled code with is_bundled = true and list the component codes in bundle_components
  - Also return the individual codes with is_bundled = false (for reference)
  - Set the bundled code at relevance_rank = 1

### 6. Uncodable Procedures
- When a procedure cannot be mapped, return: code_value = "UNCODABLE", confidence = 0.00, is_bundled = false

## Output Rules
- Call map_cpt_codes exactly once
- Return one result per input procedure_id
- Never invent codes; if uncertain, lower the confidence score
- Never include PII in justification text
- Flag confidence < 0.80 implicitly — the calling system will route for manual review
